What I would do is use a `Notification`. `Notification`s allow different parts of your app to communicate with one another. First, add an observer within whatever class your alert controller is created within:

```swift
class myClass: UIViewController {
    override func viewDidLoad() {
        super.viewDidLoad()
        NotificationCenter.default.addObserver(self, selector: #selector(showAlertController), name: &quot;ShowAlertController&quot;, object: nil)
    }

    @objc func showAlertController() {
        //Within this function, add the code that will show the alert controller
    }
}
```

Now, from any other view controller within your application, you can post to the `Notification` named &quot;ShowAlertController&quot; and this `showAlertController()` method will be called:

```swift
class someViewController {

    //Pressing this button should make the alert controller appear
    @IBAction buttonPressed(_ sender: Any) {
        NotificationCenter.default.post(name: &quot;ShowAlertController&quot;, object: nil)
    }
}
```

Its hard to say that this approach will work for you, as I am not sure the context in which the code you provided is being used, but assuming you have some sort of containing view controller, within which other view controllers are contained, then this approach should work for you.

Ideally, you would want to make an extension to `UIViewController` like Sh_Khan suggested, but if you have to, within one class, reference methods from another class, `Notification`s are one solution.

