## 1) ensure PHPUnit is converting errors, warnings, and notices

&gt; By default, PHPUnit converts PHP errors, warnings, and notices that are triggered during the execution of a test to an exception. Using these exceptions, you can, for instance, expect a test to trigger a PHP error as shown in Example 2.12.
&gt;
&gt; &amp;mdash; [Testing PHP Errors](https://phpunit.readthedocs.io/en/8.3/writing-tests-for-phpunit.html#testing-php-errors)

## 2) Ensure PHP&#39;s error reporting is set

&gt; PHP’s [error_reporting](https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.error-reporting.php) runtime configuration can limit which errors PHPUnit will convert to exceptions. If you are having issues with this feature, be sure PHP is not configured to suppress the type of errors you’re testing.
&gt;
&gt; &amp;mdash; [Testing PHP Errors](https://phpunit.readthedocs.io/en/8.3/writing-tests-for-phpunit.html#testing-php-errors)

